If `"practice_id"` in the JWT is really `4ef4febe-b026-439d-abd9-d6477b4870f6`, then the server expects **`storage_key` to match this exactly** (with **no** extra spaces):

`4ef4febe-b026-439d-abd9-d6477b4870f6/uploads/audio/<same UUID as media_id>`

The API builds that from the **`practice_id` claim as a string** (trimmed only — no case normalization):

```277:285:c:\Users\Ken Levy\OneDrive\Documents\Business\Ohana\Memories\apps\api\src\app.ts
function readStringClaim(payload: JWTPayload, claimName: string): string | null {
  const rawClaim = payload[claimName];
  if (typeof rawClaim !== "string") {
    return null;
  }

  const value = rawClaim.trim();
  return value.length > 0 ? value : null;
}
```

So if you still get **“does not match expected signed audio key”** even though the UUID “looks” right, check:

1. **Case** — The comparison is case-sensitive. If the JWT has uppercase hex (e.g. `4EF4FEBE-...`) but Postman sends lowercase in `storage_key`, it will fail (and the opposite).

2. **`media_id` vs path** — The last segment of `storage_key` must be **character-for-character** the same as `media_id`.

3. **Same token** — The Bearer token on `POST .../memories` must be the one whose payload you inspected (not an old env / different user).

4. **Copy/paste noise** — Leading/trailing space or a wrong slash in Postman (e.g. double `/`) breaks equality.

**Practical fix:** Call `POST /api/v1/uploads/audio/sign` with that same token and paste the returned `storage_key` and `media_id` into the memory body. That removes guesswork about practice id string and UUID casing.

If you want, paste (redacted) your exact `storage_key` and `media_id` from the failing request and whether the JWT uses upper- or lowercase UUIDs; we can spot a mismatch quickly.

